## Rules of Engagement

1. **Verify before implementing** — RPC method names, params, and response fields change; check docs for the target Fiber node version.
2. **Cross-reference showcase projects** — e.g. [Fiber Dashboard](https://www.fiber.world/showcase), [Fiber Studio](https://www.fiber.world/showcase) for operator-tool patterns relevant to FiberGuard.
3. **Prefer official SDK** — wrap or extend `@ckb-ccc/fiber` in `packages/fiber-rpc` rather than reimplementing JSON-RPC from scratch unless there is a clear reason.
4. **Cite sources** — when explaining protocol behavior to the user, link to the relevant doc section.
5. **Debug with docs** — map raw RPC errors to documented failure modes (channels, payments, routing) before writing diagnostic copy.
6. **VS Code extension** — follow [VS Code Extension API](https://code.visualstudio.com/api) for `apps/vscode`; do not guess contribution points, activation events, or API usage. See subsection below.

## VS Code Extension (`apps/vscode`)

When building or debugging the FiberGuard VS Code extension, use the official [Extension API docs](https://code.visualstudio.com/api) as the source of truth.

Consult these sections as needed:

| Task | Doc section |
|------|-------------|
| First-time setup, anatomy, Hello World | [Get Started](https://code.visualstudio.com/api/get-started/your-first-extension) |
| Commands, tree views, webviews, notifications | [Extension Guides](https://code.visualstudio.com/api/extension-guides/overview) — especially [Command](https://code.visualstudio.com/api/extension-guides/command), [Tree View](https://code.visualstudio.com/api/extension-guides/tree-view) |
| Sidebars, status bar, command palette UX | [UX Guidelines](https://code.visualstudio.com/api/ux-guidelines/overview) |
| `package.json` contributions, activation | [Extension Manifest](https://code.visualstudio.com/api/references/extension-manifest), [Contribution Points](https://code.visualstudio.com/api/references/contribution-points), [Activation Events](https://code.visualstudio.com/api/references/activation-events) |
| API types and methods | [VS Code API Reference](https://code.visualstudio.com/api/references/vscode-api) |
| Testing, bundling, publishing | [Testing Extensions](https://code.visualstudio.com/api/working-with-extensions/testing-extension), [Bundling](https://code.visualstudio.com/api/working-with-extensions/bundling-extension), [Publishing](https://code.visualstudio.com/api/working-with-extensions/publishing-extension) |
| Code samples | [vscode-extension-samples](https://github.com/microsoft/vscode-extension-samples) |

Extension-specific FiberGuard conventions remain in `vscode-extension.mdc`; protocol and RPC docs take precedence for Fiber logic, VS Code docs for editor integration.


## Hackathon: Gone in 60ms

**Always align scope, features, and deliverables with the official announcement:**
https://talk.nervos.org/t/gone-in-60ms-fiber-network-infrastructure-hackathon-announcement/10418

Re-read this page when scoping work, prioritizing features, or preparing submission materials. Full rules also live on the CKBoost campaign page linked from the announcement.

### Mission & boundaries

| Rule | Implication for FiberGuard |
|------|----------------------------|
| **Infrastructure only** — not consumer apps built on top | FiberGuard is operator/developer **tooling**, not a wallet, game, or merchant product |
| Mission: *"Build reusable infrastructure that makes Fiber easier to use, integrate, operate, or productise"* | Prioritize reusable packages (`diagnostics`, `fiber-rpc`) and clear integration paths for other builders |
| Key question: *Does this help future developers, wallets, merchants, services, or users interact with Fiber more easily?* | Every feature should answer this; cut vanity UI that doesn't improve Fiber reliability or debuggability |
| **Part 1** of a broader initiative — apps hackathon comes later | Stay in the infrastructure lane; don't pivot into checkout, games, or end-user micropayment apps |

### Submission category

FiberGuard targets **Category 2: Node, Routing, Cross-Chain, and Diagnostics Infrastructure**.

Relevant example directions from the announcement:

- Node dashboards (health, peers, channels, connectivity)
- Payment failure diagnostics and structured error reporting
- Route confidence, routing analytics, payment simulation
- Local testing / developer tooling for Fiber payment scenarios
- Alerting for unhealthy nodes, weak routes, peer or channel issues

Do **not** reposition FiberGuard as Category 1 (wallet UX) or Category 3 (merchant/LSP/checkout) unless explicitly requested.

### In scope vs out of scope

**In scope:** diagnostics, monitoring, can-i-pay checks, route simulation, actionable recommendations, VS Code dev tooling, open-source reusable libraries.

**Out of scope for this hackathon:** custodial wallets, merchant checkout flows, LSP marketplaces, on/off-ramping, consumer-facing payment apps, purely mocked demos without real Fiber RPC integration.

### Submission deliverables (plan toward these)

Each submission must include — track progress in README and repo:

1. Project summary and **selected category** (Category 2)
2. Team members
3. **Open-source repository** with runnable code
4. **Demo link** or runnable demo instructions + hosted demo
5. **Video demonstration**
6. Technical breakdown
7. Explanation of the **Fiber infrastructure gap** addressed
8. Future roadmap
9. AI allowance claim ($20 rebate), if applicable

Be explicit in docs about what is **fully working** vs **mocked/simulated** vs **production follow-up**.

### Judging criteria — optimize for

- Functional completeness and technical soundness
- User flow and experience (operator/developer, not end consumer)
- Relevance to Fiber infrastructure and usefulness to other builders
- Reusability, integration potential, maintainability
- Documentation quality and practical value
- Fit within Category 2 and potential for continued development

Strong submissions should realistically become part of the wider Fiber stack — prefer solid, documented, reusable components over hacky one-offs.

### AI usage (hackathon policy)

AI may be used for research, development, and documentation. Maintain a **human-driven feedback loop and testing** — purely AI-generated projects score poorly. FiberGuard code must be functionally tested against a real Fiber node where possible.

### Timeline (reference)

- Hackathon: **1 July – 15 July** (submission deadline **15 July 23:59 UTC**)
- Platform: **CKBoost**; pre-registration required; testnet CKB from Nervos Pudge Faucet

